article.headline: Duke wins 34th straight conference game
article.linkText: 'Warrior' Beard powers Duke to rout of Virginia
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Alana Beard is used to being roughed up by
opponents, so she's ready whenever the game gets physical.

	   The All-American scored 24 points, and No. 2 Duke used a 10-0
second-half run to pull away for a 75-48 victory over Virginia on
Monday night.

	   Iciss Tillis added 17 points for the Blue Devils (22-1, 10-0
ACC), who won their 34th straight conference game.

	   Cherisse Graham scored 11 to lead Virginia (10-12, 4-7) before
fouling out with 1:17 to play. She was one of two Cavaliers to foul
out in a game that featured 49 fouls and 44 free-throw attempts.

	   "It was a good thing both teams maintained their poise overall,
because it could have become very ugly,'' Duke coach Gail
Goestenkors said. "It was a very rough game. We lost our poise for
just a little bit. Several teams have tried to do that to us, but
we adjusted.''

	   Beard went 6-for-12 from the field with six rebounds and six
assists. She also went 11-for-13 from the free-throw line.

	   "I guess the strategy of some teams is to knock me down a few
times,'' Beard said. "But I'm tough, I can handle it.
	   
"I'm a warrior, not a princess.''

	   The Cavaliers cut the deficit to 42-38 on Anna Crosswhite's
3-pointer with 12:46 left, but Duke responded with 10 straight
points over the next 4½ minutes. Beard had six points in the spurt,
including consecutive layups to end the run.

	   Duke went 5-for-9 from the floor and 12-for-16 from the
free-throw line over the final 7:26 to seal the victory. Duke
closed the game with an 11-0 run as Virginia missed its last eight
shots.

	   "We just could not make shots over the last 12 minutes of the
game,'' Virginia's Debbie Ryan said. "Duke's defense was
instrumental in that to a certain extent, but most of it was us.''

	   Duke shot 51 percent, including 13-of-21 in the second half.
Virginia shot 29 percent and went 7-of-30 after the break. Duke
also converted 21 turnovers into 23 points.

	   Beard scored 10 points in the first half and Tillis had nine to
help the Blue Devils take a 33-24 halftime lead. The players each
had two baskets in the opening 4½ minutes to spark Duke to a 16-4
lead.

	   After making six of its first nine shots, Duke made just eight
of the next 21 to let Virginia back into the game. The Cavaliers
got to 29-24 with 2:02 left in the half before the Blue Devils
stretched the lead back to nine.
